A review of ice production from different parts of the continent found that Canada produced a very large quantity of ice at different times.

In February 2007, the Canadian government issued an updated report which concluded that the country produced less ice on average than the United States produced.

"Of the countries surveyed, Canada produced most of its ice in November 2007. In February, Canadian energy companies produced a total of 26.2 million cubic metres of ice over the course of about 30 years and thus provide an equivalent amount for the entire Canadian summer ice sheet," explains a press release of the government's Public Works Agency (PPS).

As an ice producer: Why are we making such a bad deal with the U.S. – and Australia?

The U.S. is Canada's top producer, with a combined total of 28.8 million liters of ice every September. The American ice supply was a mere 4 percent of the total supply as of June 2007, according to NPD's own 2017 Energy Information Administration (EIA). The U.S. produced only 24.4 million liters of ice in March 2007.

Canada, which accounts for 56 percent of annual ice sales, supplied 28.4 million tons of ice in March 2007, and Canada imports a surplus of 38 million litres of ice every October, January, and June. Canada currently imports some 70 percent of its ice in January, June and August, according to NPD.

Canadian dairy farmers, which are major producers of raw milk/milk, produced 1.3 million gallons of ice in March 2007. Despite the government's promise to keep ice production low, dairy farmers in the country actually supply less ice every day in April. They supply 37 percent of the supply with no ice to be used up.

As this ice-making sector continues to grow, a study by the Natural Resources Institute of Canada (NARAI) shows that, on average, we are importing the same amount of ice every week.

Since 2016, the Canadian ice industry has also grown in proportion to Canadians' economic activity, according to the 2017 NARAI report:

In 2016, Canada exported a total of $12.5 billion to the Canadian economy. In 2017, Canada exported $4.6 billion to the United States. On average, Canada imports nearly 300 million litres of ice daily at a time

In November 2016, Canada exported a total of $12.5 billion to the United States.

In 2016, Canada exported a total of $11.3 billion to the United States. Canada has also become the world's second-largest exporter of raw dairy products. In 2016, Canada exported $3.8 billion to the United States. In 2017, Canada exported $4.2 billion to the United States.

The Canada Hockey League brings a new ice-age mentality to hockey. On November 4, 2017, there was a major ice-age game held by the Vancouver Canucks. In 2017, hockey was the No. 1 sport in North America and in Canada. It was the third season in a row that Canada has had an ice-age game for about the past six years. Hockey players, even fans of hockey clubs like Toronto, Calgary and Montreal, celebrate at the All-Star Game during a tournament celebrating Canada's National Hockey League champions: Canada. It has hosted the annual hockey fans' association or an association called the Canadian Hockey League.

A similar phenomenon exists across the world – the United States is home to 42 of the more than 100 hockey-related hockey game matches held every year. This is called the U.S. ice hockey league.

All the way from San Jose, California to Winnipeg and then Canada to Las Vegas, most of the fans in the U.S. have come from all over the globe, including the United States and the United Kingdom. In January 2015, the NFL played Ottawa Senators in the inaugural Canadian National Hockey League Playoffs. In December 2016, the NBA played San Jose Sharks and Los Angeles Kings in the finals at the same time. The NHL has become the world's second-leading hockey game, a phenomenon seen as a great motivator towards international fans.

Canadian ice-age culture was created by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau to create national-level hockey in a country whose ice age has been reduced to less than 3 months by the U.S. Ice Hockey Association.

The U.S. ice hockey league began in the U.S. in 1924 and played regular season hockey in the 50s but didn't become a national team until the 1950s. Canadian baseball first developed a long line of hockey stars. During the 50s, when the NHL played the National Basketball Association (NBA), hockey was popular as well as baseball
